Are the most important variables similar for the regression and classification tasks?

Based on the results above, {xw03} is the most important variables in both the regression and classification models.

Does one of the sentiment derived feature types dominate the most important variables?

Based on the parts before, the variables begin with xw_ and xn_ dominate most, especially {xw_03,xw_01,xn_01}.
Based on the data description, the variables begin with xw_ is word count derived features. the number of word count is large means that the customer prefers to spend a lot of time on the product.

Does one of the sentiment derived feature types appear to be not helpful at all?

Based on the parts before, most variables which begin withxb_,xs_ and xa_ are not helpful at all.

Based on your modeling results, do you feel these sentiment derived features are helpful at predicting the outputs? Essentially, do you feel the model results are good and was I right about the relationship between report sentiment and the outputs?

Based on my results, I think most of the sentiment derived features are helpful at predicting the outputs, especially those begin with xw_ and xn_, even though some have nothing to do with the result.
Therefore, since the accuracy of classification is above 0.82 for most of the classification models, and the rmse of regression models is very low, I think we can consider the model results are good enough. However, since the data is close to imbalanced,( the probability of event is only 18%, while the data will be considered imbalanced when the probability is above 15%), I think if I have more time to do some processing to reduce the condition of imbalancing, the model can be better and the result can be better.

I prefer to use the RF regression model.

tidy_predict <- function(mod, xnew)
{
  pred_df <- predict(mod, xnew, interval = "confidence") %>% 
    as.data.frame() %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
    select(pred = fit, ci_lwr = lwr, ci_upr = upr) %>% 
    bind_cols(predict(mod, xnew, interval = 'prediction') %>% 
                as.data.frame() %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
                select(pred_lwr = lwr, pred_upr = upr))
  xnew %>% bind_cols(pred_df)
}
varImp(fit_rf_additive_tune)%>%plot(top=20)
